Restore the ability to do one-shot upgrades from the versions of npm
bundled with Node 0.8 to npm@3, which simplifies using Travis with old
Node and new npm, for compatibility testing purposes. Older versions of
npm repack packages on install, which works poorly with the way npm@3
handles bundledDependencies with flat trees.

Dexie.Syncable version 0.1 (not tested yet)

The Dexie.Syncable addon enables two-way syncronization with a remote
server. The addon is dependant on Dexie.Observable and a custom
implementation of the ISyncProtocol API defined in
Dexie.Syncable.SyncProtocolAPI.js.

There are examples in
sampes/remote-sync/websocket/WebSocketSyncProtocol.js and
WebSocketSyncServer.js. Currently these examples are not yet tested. The
aim is to create a unit test using these samples and verifying the
entire sync framework.

Differentiating syncedRevision from baseRevision

After a review of the sync API I found out that there is a difference
between baseRevision and syncedRevision.

BaseRevision is what the given changes are based on while syncedRevision
is the revision that we request the server to give changes from.

This commit updates the API spec, the sample code and the framework
(Dexie.Syncable.js) to differentiate these.

Bugfixes after unit testing Dexie.Syncable

Ran all Dexie tests with Dexie.Syncable applied and a dummy

Dexie.Syncable.js: Days of testing and bugfixing

Tested Dexie.Syncable by creating a sync provider towards the sync
server of my current project. The goal is to migrate my app from using
localStorage to be using indexedDB. I will replace the current db
framework built on localStorage and ajax syncing to be based on Dexie
and Dexie.Syncable.

When committing this, the framework is working as expected with my
application. The application runs in two different windows so one of the
windows becomes the master node that is responsible of doing the sync
calls to the server. There were errors in forms of dead-locks due to the
lack of db.vip() in some places.

Still, one of the unit tests for Dexie.Syncable fails. Need to check
what is wrong and do another commit soon.

Bugfixed and migrated Syncable&Observable to new transaction method

Nested transactions derive transaction.source

Nested transaction will by default derive the source property from its
parent transaction. The source property can be used to mark the changes
a originated from a certiain source. It can be used when subscribing to
the db.on('changes') event that Dexie.Observable adds to Dexie. When
changes arrive the subscriber may inspect change.source to see if the
change was initiated by itself and the ignore that change. It is also
used by Dexie.Syncable to mark certain changes as originating from a
remote node so that the same changes are never sent back to that node.

This commit makes a nested transaction derive the source property from
its parent transaction by default. This makes it easier for application
code to know that the source property needs only to be set on parent
transaction and all nested function will derive it no matter whether
they enclose their operations within a nested transaction or not.

Also, lowering the NODE_TIMEOUT from 30 to 20 seconds.

New use case for db.on('ready')

Now if calling db.on('ready') when db is already open, the subscriber
will be fired immediately. That way, it is now possible to use the event
more like the jquery ready event - no matter if database has opened or
not, it will launch when ready to launch.

This means that the on('ready') event differs from how other events
behave. Will soon update wiki documentation to reflect this.

#75 Wrong order of changes Dexie.Observable/Syncable

Wrong order of changes Dexie.Observable/Syncable when using sub
transactions.

Redesigned Dexie.Observable to add the changes in the same tick as the
CREATE/UPDATE/DELETE  operation is taking place instead of waiting for
this.onsuccess. Reason is that transaction may be locked when
this.onsuccess is triggered, resulting in that the change revision is
added later than it should have beem and occur after other changes that
actually occurred later.

Issue #76 Web Worker support for addons as well

Addons Dexie.Syncable and Dexie.Observable made compliant with
WebWorkers also. Made it possible to test that in the unit test suite
when including the addons.

Bumped version to 1.1

Deprecated Dexie.spawn() and replaced it with Dexie.ignoreTransaction()
which is more descriptive. Main reason is that spawn() could be
associated with Task.js spawn() that has another meaning.  Dexie.spawn()
will still be able to use but will log a warning to console that is has
been deprecated.

Next release will be an 1.1 release because of the deprecation of
Dexie.spawn() as well as the changed behavior when including Dexie with
requirejs - before it would still put itself into window but now it will
act as a real amd module.
